<article>
    <h1>One ring to rule them all: 12,638-di&#xAD;a&#xAD;mond cre&#xAD;ation sets world record</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201206/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-06"><time>2020-12-06</time></a>
        - <span>WORLD</span>
        - <span role="byline">PHOTOS: AGENCE FRANCE-PRESSE</span>
    </section>

    <p>An elab­o­rate flo­ral-shaped ring sport­ing 12,638 tiny di­a­monds has earned a place in the Guin­ness World Records – but its In­dian cre­ator has no plans to sell his price­less de­sign just yet.</p>
    <p>Called The Marigold – The Ring Of Pros­per­ity, the chunky cir­cu­lar band weighs a lit­tle over 165g.</p>
    <p>“It’s wear­able and com­fort­able,” said 25-year-old Harshit Bansal, who de­scribed his au­da­cious cre­ation as a dream project.</p>
    <p>He said he got the idea for the ring two years ago while study­ing jew­ellery de­sign in the western city of Su­rat, In­dia’s di­a­mond hub.</p>
    <p>“My tar­get was al­ways more than 10,000 di­a­monds. I trashed many de­signs and con­cepts over the years to fi­nally zero in on this,” he said.</p>
    <p>In a state­ment, his com­pany said that each tiny pe­tal in the ring’s eight-layer flower de­sign is unique.</p>
    <p>Mr Bansal said he has al­ready turned away re­quests from prospec­tive buy­ers.</p>
    <p>“We have no plans of sell­ing it right now,” he said. “It’s a mat­ter of pride for us. It’s price­less.”</p>
    <p>The pre­vi­ous record de­ter­mined by Guin­ness, also set in In­dia, was for a ring con­tain­ing 7,801 di­a­monds.</p>

